    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-02-09T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-02-09T07:00:00-05:00" n="258"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d258">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">760D.61/1081: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-02-09T15:00:00+03:00"
                            >February 9, 1940—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 9—1:11 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>161. My telegram No. 159, February 9, 1 p.m.<note n="59" xml:id="d258fn59">
                        <hi rend="italic">Post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_543">p. 543</ref>.</note> In
                    the course of my conversation with Ritter<note n="60" xml:id="d258fn60">Karl
                        Ritter, Ambassador on special assignment in the German Foreign Office, in
                        charge of economic warfare questions, temporarily in Moscow.</note> he
                    confirmed the fact reported in my <pb facs="0301" n="289" xml:id="pg_289"/>
                    telegram under reference that the German Government had recently offered to
                    mediate between the Finnish and Soviet Governments but had failed to elicit a
                    favorable response from the Soviet Government. He expressed the opinion that the
                    Soviet Government now regarded the Finnish war primarily in the light of its
                    military prestige and consequently was determined for this reason to achieve at
                    least some measures of military success before even giving consideration to the
                    possibilities of a settlement by negotiation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
